                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I'm not seeing the problem with Vexing Banshees at 55, provided you've got Virtue, and KEI. ( Please don't shoot me until you hear me out. )<br /><br /><br />Spell Lineup Is As Follows:<br /><br />Harmshield<br />Feign Death<br />Bond of Death<br />Splurt<br />Shadowbond<br />Renew Bones<br />Deflux<br />Shackle of Spirit<br /><br />___________________<br /><br /><br />Pull the Banshee with Splurt - I avoided getting summoned with Splurt pulls, 90% of the time -- the reason being that Splurt doesn't do enough damage to the non-snared Banshee to warrant a summons, by the time it arrives within aggro range to the Augmentationed Level 49 Pet ( taunt on ), who is parked beside the Hedge. Sick pet while the Banshee is still about 100 ft. away -- the pet should engage the Banshee, and with the proper timing he will gain aggro right as the Banshee runs past the big rock near the Hedge.<br /><br /><br />Immediately cast Shackle of Spirit -- the pet cannot survive an un-slowed Banshee for more than twelve seconds. Assuming Shackle is resisted, it'd be a good idea to Harmshield, and click the tombstone to zone out. It was resisted about 30% of the time at 56, so the odds of it sticking should still be in a 55's favor. In any event, it is possible to slow the Banshee at 55, and once the Banshee is slowed, the fight is in the bag.<br /><br /><br />Bond of Death the Banshee, and then Shadowbond the pet -- follow that up by chain-casting Renew Bones until the pet is at about 80% health. Bond, Shadowbond, and Splurt should've cooked up a big batch of aggro by now, so Feign Death to clear it, then sit and meditate. In almost all cases, the pet held aggro. You should be at about 70% mana at this point. Shadowbond will be wearing down by now, so refresh it, refresh Bond of Death, Deflux once to go back to 100% health, and then punch another Renew Bones -- the pet should be at around 75%, + or - depending on how many Drains he's managed to proc.<br /><br /><br />Depending on the necromancer's manapool, I'd suggest dropping another Splurt to expedite things, but some would rather keep that extra mana available to heal the pet in case of emergency. In any event, you'll be losing health per tick from Shadowbond, even with Bond of Death in effect, but the health loss should be minimized due to the 20 or 30 health per tick you're *not* losing from Lich. It is important to keep Shadowbond on the pet at all times, and it is also important to keep Bond of Death up at all times.<br /><br /><br />When the Banshee is at about 40% health, I tended to be at around 60% mana. At this point, I would move into melee range with the Banshee, take one or two hits, then back up and Deflux -- I allowed Shadowbond to wear at this point, but continued to renew BoDeath, and Renewed Bones when the pet looked a little -too- badly damaged ( I.E., 65%~ )<br /><br /><br />Between Bond of Death, and taking a hit from the Banshee now and again, I was able to drop a Vexed Banshee at 56, with about 45% mana remaining. I thought it was important to note that KEI is a better choice when dealing with these, as Lich + Shadowbond eat around 144 health per tick, while BoDeath regenerates about 80 health per tick. The twenty health per tick saved adds up, and the extra mana to the manapool via KEI's intelligence bonus, plus the 150 raw mana added, is enough to punch out an extra BoDeath, assuming one's specialization skill is up to par ( which it should be ).<br /><br /><br />At 61, Banshees are nothing more than big bags of health points. I pull with Undead Slow, which does get me summoned, but then the 61 pet taunts the thing, and it's over -- I Vexing Mordinia the poor spook, Shadowbond the pet, Splurt the spook, Feign Death to reduce aggro, Funeral Pyre the spook, Feign again, and then sit and meditate, renewing Shadowbond as needed -- I use Demi-Lich at this point, because Vexing can keep up with Shadowbond and Demi-Lich. Renew Bones isn't necessary -- the thing dies by the time the pet is down to about 65%. I end battles with around 80% mana, and 90% health.<br /><br /><br />One other thing -- You're instructing this poor guy to try sticking poison and disease DoTs to YELLOW CON undead mobs? You're a real brain surgeon, aren'tcha? I'm 61, and I cannot - repeat, CANNOT - land Dark Plague, which is a -50 DR Check, on these things, and they con blue.<br /><br /><br />This is something you should've learned a long, long time ago. When the mob is undead, stick with magic-based spells. Diseasing something that's already a walking pile of pestilence and plague isn't gonna work too well.<br /><br /><br />Common sense, people -- invest in some. It really helps.<br /><br /><br />Good luck to those who're attempting these at 55 or 56 -- it's more than possible to kill them at that level, but for experience, stick with aggrokiting the trash near the zone-in. That's much more efficient, experience-wise, and KEI is totally unnecessary.<br /><br /><br />Ciao.<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> - Baron Demetrii Hopeslayer<br />- Level 62 Warlock<br />- Follower of Cazic-Thule<br />' Life is not the best of things, nor is Death the worst. '</span></font></td>
                    </tr>
